			<h5>Abstract</h5>
			<p>
				This final project will focus on exploring computing ethics in Japan. Japanese ethics are highly influenced by Buddhism, Shintoism, and Confucianism, including business ethics. Thus computing ethics are necessarily entangled with religious thought. As with many Asian cultures, Japanese society is collectivist, focusing on the needs and rights of the group over those of the individual. Duty to one’s groups is an important ethical concept, as is “fairness.” This is relevant to business as it concerns the relationships between employees and the business hierarchy, as well as what actions are taken and when. Vital to the project will be an exploration of the Japanese Internet and government attitudes toward regulation. In general, the Japanese Internet considered “free,” following laws allowing freedom of the press and of speech, though there is a law instructing internet service providers to self-regulate and take down objectionable content from their servers. “Objectionable content” includes illegal material, defamation, violations of privacy, and intellectual property infringement. Internet access is not restricted to anyone and there is currently no evidence of the Japanese government monitoring its citizens’ activities on the internet. This project will explore this system and make connections to Japanese ethics. Overall, the project will focus in particular on the effects of religious thought and collectivist society on Japanese computing ethics, as well as outline the ethics particular to the Japanese business world, Japanese intellectual property law, Japanese perspectives on privacy and data collection, and the interaction of Japanese ethics and other ethical systems in international business. 
			</p>
			
